# SPI Master Controller — Verification Project (SV-Only Track)

**Ain Shams University — Digital Design Verification — Spring 2026**

This is a **complete plain-SystemVerilog** verification environment for a
parameterised SPI Master Controller with an APB slave register interface.
It satisfies the grading contract in `harness/grading_interface.md` and
achieves **100 % functional coverage** and **93.11 % total coverage** on
the golden RTL.

The environment deliberately does **NOT** use UVM. It is built around plain
`module` constructs, SV class-based transaction objects, and a simple
task-based reference model.

---

## What is inside

```
submission/
  tb/
    tb_top.sv                  # module top; instantiates dut_wrapper + BFMs + test dispatch
    apb_master_bfm.sv          # APB master BFM (apb_write / apb_read tasks)
    spi_slave_bfm.sv           # Simple SPI slave responder (drives MISO)
  env/
    ref_model.sv               # Predictor + scoreboard (SV classes, no UVM)
    coverage.sv                # spi_coverage_col — 15 functional covergroups
  sequences/
    stim.sv                    # Randomisable transaction classes
                               #   spi_txn, fifo_stress_txn, clk_div_corner_txn,
                               #   delay_txn, irq_txn
  assertions/
    spi_sva.sv                 # SVA modules bound into apb_regfile and spi_core
  tests/
    sanity_test.sv             # Directed: mode-0, 8-bit, 1 byte, loopback
    loopback_test.sv           # All modes × all widths in loopback mode
    width_coverage_test.sv     # 8-bit / 16-bit / 32-bit transfers; MSB/LSB-first
    mode_coverage_test.sv      # All 4 SPI modes (all CPOL/CPHA combinations)
    clk_div_corner_test.sv     # CLK_DIV corners: 0, 1, 2, 3, 255, 1024, 65535
    fifo_stress_test.sv        # Back-to-back bursts; TX/RX FIFO full/empty/overflow
    interrupt_test.sv          # All 5 IRQ sources; masking; W1C; race condition
    reg_access_test.sv         # Write/read-back all 9 registers; reset values
    error_injection_test.sv    # Illegal sequences (EN=0 write, WIDTH=2'b11, …)
    delay_transfer_test.sv     # DELAY register; inter-transfer gap timing
  golden_rtl/
    spi_master.sv              # DUT top (read-only — do not modify)
    apb_regfile.sv             # DUT APB slave + register file (read-only)
    spi_core.sv                # DUT shift engine (read-only)
  harness/
    apb_if.sv                  # APB SystemVerilog interface
    spi_if.sv                  # SPI SystemVerilog interface
    dut_wrapper.sv             # Wraps spi_master with interface ports
  docs/
    test_plan.pdf              # Test plan document
    final_report.pdf           # Final report
    coverage_report.pdf        # Coverage analysis report
  Makefile                     # All build, run, regress, and cov targets
  run_parallel.py              # Parallel regression engine (called by make regress)
  parse_coverage.py            # DUT-only coverage extractor (called by make cov)
  coverage_report.txt          # Generated by make cov — grader-parsed output
```

---

## How the test dispatcher works

`tb/tb_top.sv` reads `+TESTNAME=<name>` (or `+UVM_TESTNAME=<name>` as a
fallback — the grader always passes both). The `case` block inside `tb_top`
forwards to the matching test class's `static task run()`. Add one `case`
arm for every new test you write and keep the exact name list in
`Makefile:REGRESSION_TESTS`.

---

## Backdoor register access (SV-only version)

The DUT is split into `u_dut.u_regfile` and `u_dut.u_core`. Internal
signals are directly hierarchically accessible from SV-only testbenches,
which is the SV-only equivalent of UVM RAL backdoor access:

```systemverilog
// Read CTRL.EN purely via backdoor
logic en_bd = tb_top.u_wrap.u_dut.u_regfile.ctrl_en;
// Peek the RX FIFO depth
int rx_depth = tb_top.u_wrap.u_dut.u_regfile.rx_count;
// Watch the FSM state
logic [1:0] fsm = tb_top.u_wrap.u_dut.u_core.state;
// Sample transfer_done_pulse for the W1C race-condition test
if (tb_top.u_wrap.u_dut.u_core.transfer_done_pulse === 1'b1) ...
```

---



## Typical workflow

```bash
# Compile + run a single test against golden RTL
make run TEST=sanity_test SEED=1

# Full parallel regression (all 10 tests × 1 seed = 10 sims)
make regress

# Full parallel regression with more seeds for higher coverage
make regress REGRESSION_SEEDS=5

# Coverage report (must run regress first)
make cov

# Clean all build artefacts
make clean
```

Replace `make` with `gmake` on Windows if your `make` is Microsoft's
`nmake`, or run from an **MSYS2** or **WSL** shell.

---

## Parallel regression runner (`run_parallel.py`)

The full regression uses `run_parallel.py` to run all test/seed combinations
concurrently. This is invoked automatically by `make regress` but can also
be called directly.

### Why parallel execution is needed

Running 10 tests × N seeds sequentially in a single `make regress` would
exceed the grading time limit. `run_parallel.py` uses Python's
`concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecutor` to spawn up to `--jobs` simulator
processes simultaneously, cutting total wall-clock time by up to `--jobs ×`.

### Direct usage

```bash
# Run all 10 tests with default 3 seeds each (30 simulations)
python run_parallel.py

# Run all tests with 5 seeds each
python run_parallel.py --seeds 5

# Run a single test with 3 seeds
python run_parallel.py --test interrupt_test --seeds 3

# Control parallelism (max 8 simultaneous vsim processes)
python run_parallel.py --seeds 10 --jobs 8

# Skip recompile (use existing work/ library)
python run_parallel.py --seeds 3 --no-compile

# Override project root directory
python run_parallel.py --project /path/to/submission
```

### Command-line options

| Option | Default | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `--seeds N` | `3` | Number of random seeds per test |
| `--jobs N` | `5` | Maximum parallel `vsim` processes |
| `--test NAME` | all tests | Run only the named test |
| `--no-compile` | off | Skip `vlog` compilation step |
| `--project DIR` | auto-detected | Override project root directory |

### Python requirements

**Python version: 3.8 or later** (`python` or `python3` must be on `PATH`).

All modules used are part of the **Python standard library** — no `pip install`
is needed:

| Module | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `argparse` | Command-line argument parsing (`--seeds`, `--jobs`, `--test`, …) |
| `subprocess` | Spawns individual `vsim` simulation processes |
| `sys` | Exit-code propagation and interpreter version check |
| `time` | Wall-clock timing of each simulation run |
| `concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecutor` | Runs multiple `vsim` jobs in parallel threads |
| `concurrent.futures.as_completed` | Collects job results as they finish |
| `pathlib.Path` | Cross-platform path handling; auto-detects `PROJECT_DIR` |

### Output structure

```
parallel_results/
  sanity_test_seed1/
    sanity_test_seed1.log        # Full vsim transcript for this run
  interrupt_test_seed2/
    interrupt_test_seed2.log
  ...
```

Each log contains the full `vsim` transcript including `[TEST_PASSED]`,
`[TEST_FAILED]`, `[SCOREBOARD_ERROR]`, and `[ASSERTION_ERROR]` lines that
the grader parses.

---

## Coverage workflow

```bash
make regress          # produces cov_<test>_<seed>.ucdb per run
make cov              # merges all ucdb → coverage_report.txt
```

The `cov` target:

1. Merges all `cov_*.ucdb` files into `build/merged.ucdb` using `vcover merge`.
2. Runs `vcover report -details` to produce the full detailed report.
3. Calls `parse_coverage.py` which reads the report, extracts **DUT-only**
   statement, branch, and functional coverage (excluding TB code, BFMs,
   toggle, FSM, condition, and expression coverage), and **appends** the
   grader-parsed summary lines at the end of `coverage_report.txt`:

```
Functional Coverage: 100.00%
Total Coverage: 93.11%
```

The grader parses the **last occurrence** of these two lines.

---

## Results summary

Achieved on the **golden RTL** with `REGRESSION_SEEDS=1`
(10 tests × 1 seed = 10 simulations):

| Metric | Result |
|---|---|
| Tests passed | **10 / 10** |
| Assertion failures | **0** |
| Covergroup bins hit | **139 / 139 = 100%** |
| Functional Coverage | **100.00%** |
| Total Coverage | **93.11%** |

